{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7814c782-162b-486e-ba5c-a4e5e515101c","content":"TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively. Since the project is an `Exe`, run it with:\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nThis uses MTP's treenode filter to match only tests under the `SmsNotificationTests` class. The `--` separates `dotnet run` args from arguments passed to the test executable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c0abfcb9-2f90-4aee-ab19-20076b058249","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project (v0.6.120). TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For MTP-based runners, you filter by class using the `--treenode-filter` option.\n\nThe full class name is `Contoso.Notifications.Tests.SmsNotificationTests`.\n\nFor TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax is:\n```\ndotnet run --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nSince TUnit projects have `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`, they are run with `dotnet run` not `dotnet test` (unless using VSTest compatibility). Let me check - actually TUnit 0.6.x uses MTP natively. The command would be:\n\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nThough `dotnet test` with a class filter could work as a fallback, the native MTP approach is the standard for TUnit.\n```","outputTokens":499},"id":"e617718d-9772-4099-9174-cd59a1102aeb","timestamp":"2026-04-07T14:25:12.597Z","parentId":"3fb0f896-513d-4f97-91dc-1eeaa78f9362"}
